Bank Saint Petersburg advanced for a
third day, its longest winning streak in more than a month,
after the lender posted a sixfold jump in first-quarter profit.  The shares surged as much as 7.9 percent before closing 5.8
percent higher at 148.05 rubles by the 6:45 p.m. close in
Moscow.  Earnings climbed to 2.1 billion rubles from the same period
last year, the bank said in an e-mailed statement today.  The stock jumped as much as 8.7 percent yesterday after the
 European Bank for Reconstruction and Development  said it will
